  <section class="venues venues--plain" id="faq">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="venues__header">
        <div>
          <p class="label label--accent">Common questions</p>
          <h2 class="venues__title">What walkers actually ask</h2>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="venues__grid venues__grid--links">
        <div class="venue-card">
          <h3 class="venue-card__name">What is the best season for walking on the Peninsula?</h3>
          <p class="venue-card__signature">Autumn (March to May) and spring (September to November) are the best walking seasons. Temperatures are comfortable, crowds are manageable, and the light is excellent for photography. Summer is good for early morning walks on the clifftops before the heat and crowds arrive. Winter is underrated — the Coastal Walk in a moderate southerly swell, in the company of almost no one, is one of the Peninsula's most dramatic walk conditions. Just go prepared for cold and mud on the longer tracks.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="venue-card">
          <h3 class="venue-card__name">Is the 100km walk actually 100km?</h3>
          <p class="venue-card__signature">No — it is officially 97.5km and called the "Mornington Peninsula Walk." The "100km" name is marketing shorthand that stuck. The circuit combines the Two Bays Walking Trail, the Coastal Walk, the Point Nepean Walk, and the Bay Trail, and takes most walkers 8–10 days to complete. It is best planned in sections across multiple Peninsula visits rather than as a single continuous challenge.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="venue-card">
          <h3 class="venue-card__name">Can I walk from Sorrento to Portsea?</h3>
          <p class="venue-card__significance">Yes — the Coastal Walk and clifftop tracks connect much of the southern tip. The Farnsworth Track from London Bridge to Portsea Ocean Beach (1.5km one-way) is the clearest direct route in the Portsea direction. Wilson's Folly and other tracks extend the corridor toward Sorrento. Check current track conditions and access via Parks Victoria before combining tracks into a longer point-to-point.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="venue-card">
          <h3 class="venue-card__name">Is the Cape Schanck Lighthouse walk the same as Bushrangers Bay?</h3>
          <p class="venue-card__significance">No — these are two different experiences departing from close to the same area. The Cape Schanck boardwalk takes 20 minutes return to the lighthouse platform. The Bushrangers Bay walk is 5km return (2 hours) to the bay below the cape, departing from the same carpark. Both are worth doing. Most first-time visitors only do the boardwalk; most returning visitors say the Bushrangers Bay walk is the better experience.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

